Kinex Fit — Project Status Overview

Below is a clear snapshot of what the app is, what it does, where development stands, what’s left, and the issues we’ve been hitting. I’ve linked each point back to concrete parts of the codebase so you can see exactly where things live.

What this app is and what it does

Kinex Fit is a fitness app that:
• Authenticates users via multiple providers:
   • Apple, Google, Facebook, and email/password (see AuthViewModel, AuthService, GoogleSignInManager, FacebookSignInManager, EmailPasswordAuthService).
• Stores and manages workouts locally with offline-first behavior:
   • Local persistence via GRDB (AppDatabase, Workout, DatabaseMigratorFactory).
   • A repository layer for CRUD and live observation (WorkoutRepository).
   • A background sync queue to push local changes to the backend (SyncEngine).
• Maintains a local user profile and subscription state:
   • Local user caching and updates (UserRepository).
   • Subscription and purchase scaffolding (PurchaseValidator, StoreManager) — integrated into the environment but implementations not shown here.
• Provides an onboarding flow gated by the user’s profile flag:
   • RootView toggles OnboardingCoordinator based on user.onboardingCompleted.
• Prepares for notifications and provider callback handling:
   • NotificationManager is injected as an environment object.
   • OAuth callback handling via AppDelegate and .onOpenURL in KinexFitApp.

Key infrastructure:
• A central dependency container (AppEnvironment) wires together services and provides .live and .preview configurations.
• A clean separation of concerns between API, storage, repositories, and view models.
• Swift Concurrency throughout (async/await), plus OSLog for diagnostics.

Architecture at a glance

• App entry:
   • KinexFitApp composes the app with AppState(environment: .live), injects RootView, and forwards OAuth callbacks via .onOpenURL.
• Environment and services:
   • AppEnvironment sets up APIClient, TokenStore (Keychain or in-memory), AppDatabase, SyncEngine, and service layer types (AuthService, WorkoutRepository, UserRepository, PurchaseValidator, StoreManager, NotificationManager, GoogleSignInManager, FacebookSignInManager, EmailPasswordAuthService).
   • .preview uses in-memory storage to support SwiftUI previews.
• Data layer:
   • AppDatabase + DatabaseMigratorFactory define schema for users, workouts, body_metrics, sync_queue, and settings.
   • WorkoutRepository provides CRUD and observation with ValueObservation.
   • UserRepository manages the local user, subscription updates, onboarding flag, and account deletion (including clearing local state).
• Networking:
   • APIClient builds requests (APIRequest) and handles auth headers via TokenStore.
   • AuthService implements sign-in, token refresh, and sign-out using endpoints under /api/mobile/auth/....
   • SyncEngine reads from sync_queue, sends changes to /api/mobile/workouts, and tracks retries/exponential backoff.

Where we’re at with development

What’s implemented and functional now:
• Authentication flows:
   • Apple, Google, Facebook, and email/password flows are wired in AuthViewModel and AuthService, including error handling and provider-specific cancellation cases.
   • Session bootstrapping: AuthViewModel.checkExistingSession() restores a session from tokens and local user where possible.
   • Sign-out clears tokens and local state, including best-effort server notification.
• Offline-first storage for workouts:
   • Full CRUD and observation streams in WorkoutRepository.
   • SyncEngine infrastructure to enqueue local changes and push to backend with retries.
• User profile caching and subscription scaffolding:
   • Local user read/write (UserRepository), subscription update methods, onboarding flag.
   • Account deletion orchestrates backend delete then clears local data and tokens.
• App shell & navigation:
   • Splash → Sign-in → Onboarding → Main tabs via RootView.
   • Dependency injection via AppEnvironment is clean and preview-friendly.

