Issues we’ve been running into

These come straight from the code and are likely the root cause of current pain points:

1. Sync queue payloads can’t be decoded (date strategy mismatch)
• Where:
   • WorkoutRepository.queueSync(workout:operation:) encodes with JSONEncoder().dateEncodingStrategy = .iso8601.
   • SyncEngine.syncItem(_:) uses JSONDecoder() with default date decoding.
• Problem:
   • Default JSONDecoder expects Date encoded via .deferredToDate (a numeric timestamp), but the queue payload uses ISO8601 strings — decoding fails.
• Symptom:
   • try? JSONDecoder().decode(Workout.self, ...) returns nil and SyncError.unsupportedOperation is thrown, so items never sync and eventually get marked failed.
• Fix direction:
   • Use a single, shared JSON encoder/decoder config (ISO8601) for both queue serialization and API requests, or move queue payload to an ID-only or minimal schema and re-fetch as needed.

2. Delete operations in sync will fail to parse
• Where:
   • WorkoutRepository.queueSync(workoutId:operation:) encodes payload as {"id": "<id>"}.
   • SyncEngine.syncItem(_:) tries to decode a full Workout from payload for all operations.
• Problem:
   • For delete, payload only has an ID; decoding to Workout fails, causing unsupportedOperation.
• Fix direction:
   • Branch delete handling to decode an ID-only payload, or make payload schema explicit per operation. For DELETE, you typically don’t need a body; just the ID in the path.

3. Inconsistent date encoding for API requests
• Where:
   • SyncEngine calls APIRequest.json(path:method:body:) with a default JSONEncoder (no ISO8601).
• Problem:
   • Even if we fix queue decoding, API requests will still send dates in the default format (double since reference date) unless the server also expects that — which is unlikely.
• Fix direction:
   • Standardize a single JSONEncoder/JSONDecoder with .iso8601 for all network traffic and queue payloads. Consider centralizing in APIClient or APIRequest.

4. Database schema vs. code mismatch for user subscription tier
• Where:
   • DatabaseMigratorFactory creates a users table with a column named "tier" in migration "create-v1".
   • Code references "subscriptionTier" in AuthModels.SignInResponse.UserResponse.toUser() and in UserRepository.updateSubscription(tier:status:expiresAt:) (SQL updates subscriptionTier).
• Problem:
   • Writes to subscriptionTier will fail if the column doesn’t exist; reads/writes will be inconsistent.
• Fix direction:
   • Align schema and code. Either rename column to subscriptionTier via a migration or update code to use tier. Verify the User GRDB mapping matches the final column names.

5. Signing in with expired tokens at launch
• Where:
   • AuthViewModel.checkExistingSession() treats “has any access token” as valid and signs in if a local user exists, without refreshing.
• Problem:
   • If the token is expired, subsequent API calls will 401. Users think they’re signed in but actions fail.
• Fix direction:
   • Track token expiry (from expiresIn) and refresh at app start if close to or past expiry. Alternatively, implement API-layer 401 interception and refresh.

6. Sync running on the main actor
• Where:
   • SyncEngine.processSyncQueue() is marked @MainActor.
• Problem:
   • Network and disk I/O on the main actor risks stuttering the UI and blocking input.
• Fix direction:
   • Remove @MainActor from sync processing and isolate mutable state (e.g., guard isSyncing with an actor or serial queue).

7. DELETE requests include a body
• Where:
   • SyncEngine.syncItem(_:) sets method = .delete and body = workout for delete.
• Problem:
   • Many servers ignore DELETE bodies; it’s atypical and can cause backend issues. Given the path includes the ID, no body is needed.
• Fix direction:
   • Don’t send a body for DELETE. If the backend expects a body, standardize the schema and document it.

8. Error mapping doesn’t parse backend error payloads
• Where:
   • AuthService.mapAPIError(_:) maps only HTTP status codes. APIErrorResponse exists but is unused.
• Problem:
   • We lose actionable info like retryAfter or error codes. Users get generic errors.
• Fix direction:
   • On non-2xx, parse the response body into APIErrorResponse and map to richer AuthError cases.

9. Onboarding state may not update post-sign-in
• Where:
   • RootView sets showOnboarding only when authViewModel.authState changes to .signedIn(let user).
   • UserRepository.markOnboardingComplete() updates the DB, but authState.user isn’t automatically updated.
• Problem:
   • If onboarding completion is toggled later, UI may not reflect it until the next auth state change or app restart.
• Fix direction:
   • Observe user changes via UserRepository.observeCurrentUser() and derive onboarding state from that, or update authState when onboarding completes.

10. Previews hitting production base URL
• Where:
   • AppEnvironment.preview uses AppConfig.apiBaseURL which is currently production (https://kinexfit.com).
• Problem:
   • Even with in-memory DB, previews shouldn’t hit prod services accidentally.
• Fix direction:
   • Use a stubbed APIClient or a staging URL for previews/testing.

Immediate recommendations

• Unify JSON encoding/decoding:
   • Create a shared JSONCoder (encoder and decoder) with .iso8601 dates and use it in both APIClient and SyncEngine queue payloads.
• Fix sync delete handling:
   • For delete queue items, decode just the ID and send DELETE without a body.
• Align DB schema with code:
   • Add a migration to rename users.tier → subscriptionTier (or vice versa) and confirm User mapping matches.
• Remove @MainActor from sync processing:
   • Move shared state into an actor if needed; keep UI updates off the sync path.
• Add API-level token refresh:
   • On 401, attempt a refresh and retry once. If refresh fails, sign out.
• Improve onboarding state propagation:
   • Observe the user model for changes and drive showOnboarding from that, not just the initial sign-in snapshot.
• Introduce staging config:
   • Add AppConfig.apiBaseURL variants and wire per build configuration. Ensure previews never call prod.

